Date: Sun, 15 Feb 2004
From: Zhiru Guo <guozhiru@yahoo.com> [edited]

Avian influenza in felines
---------------------------
Re "Leopard dies from bird flu in Thailand" in ProMED-mail posting AVIAN
INFLUENZA - EASTERN ASIA (24), Fri 13 Feb 2004:
The said report is really an unusual observation, but it may not be the
first report of influenza in animals of the cat family. A paper published
in the Chinese Journal of Veterinary Science reported the isolation of
influenza A virus from specimens taken from a tiger [in 2002] that showed
clinical symptoms and died; the isolate caused severe disease and death in
experimentally infected cats (see abstract below).
Regarding the origin of the tiger virus, feeding the tiger with birds
infected with avian influenza virus should be considered one of the
possibilities. The so called "species barrier" between avian influenza
virus and mammals may be very weak, and some types of avian influenza
viruses have the potential to cross the barrier and infect other animals
directly, causing severe disease -- if those animals are exposed to
sufficient amounts of virus or through an adequate route of administration.
Consequently, the public -- especially in AI-affected rural areas -- should
be educated not to feed any animals sick or dead chickens. I believe it is
relatively common for the village farmers who breed free-range chickens to
feed their dogs, pigs, etc. their sick or dead chickens. The importance of
personal protection while handling sick or dead chicken also deserves to be
stressed.
The above-mentioned paper was published in Chinese; I have translated the
abstract into English:
XIA Xian-zhu, GAO Yu-wei, HU Rong-liang et al. The First Finding of Tiger
Influenza by Virus Isolation and Specific Gene Amplification. Chinese
Journal of Veterinary Science, March 2003, Vol. 23, No.2, Pages 107-110.
Abstract: An influenza virus-like isolate was obtained from the specimen of
a tiger [which] died [in 2002] of high fever, anorexia, and [seizures]. This
virus was confirmed to be influenza virus by characteristics of its
morphology, physiochemistry, biology, and serology.
Further analysis was performed by amplification of the specific nucleic
acid [sequence] of the influenza virus nucleoprotein gene. A 464-bp cDNA
fragment, being amplified from both the virus cell culture and the
suspension of specimens, was compared with the published sequences of
influenza virus types A, B, and C, with homology of 84.9, 35.0, and 24.8
percent, respectively, indicating that the virus is an influenza virus type
A isolate. This virus has been designated as A/tiger/Harbin/01/2002.
3 domestic cats 3 months of age were infected with the virus by intravenous
inoculation. One of the infected cats survived the infection and the other
2 were seriously sick and eventually died of the infection. The ill cats
presented similar clinical signs and pathological changes (characterized by
pneumonia) to those of the tiger.
This is the first report [demonstrating] that influenza virus type A exists
in tigers.
--
Dr.Zhiru Guo
Laboratory of Animal Virology
Veterinary Institute
Changchun University of Agriculture and Animal Sciences
5333 Xi'an Road, Changchun 130062
P. R. of China
<guozhiru@yahoo.com>
[Dr Zhiru Guo is gratefully acknowledged for the reference and commentary.
The information provided in the paper underlines 2 important points: first,
the alleged potential of a (probably) avian influenza virus to cross the
species barrier and infect felines. Second, the possibility that the
described influenza virus was prevalent in China's poultry during 2002. It
will be important to determine the genetic profile of this isolate and its
relationship to other isolates, and particularly to the virus involved in
the current pandemic and to strain(s) involved in human cases.
Chinese-reading subscribers can view/download a pdf copy of the said paper at:
<http://zgsyxb.periodicals.net.cn/default.html>.
- Mod.AS]
