Date: 14 Feb 2004
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: News24.Com, 14 Feb 2004 [edited]
<http://www.news24.com/News24/World/News/0,,2-10-1462_1483802,00.html>

Bird flu kills exotic species
-----------------------------
After killing millions of chickens and ducks across Asia, bird flu is
feared to have jumped to more exotic species, possibly killing a leopard
and cranes in Thailand and pheasants in Taiwan.
The UN Food and Agriculture Organisation warned that the disease -- which
has killed 14 people in Vietnam and 5 in Thailand -- still has not been
controlled in several Asian countries. "Cambodia, China, Indonesia, and
Laos continue to report new outbreaks in poultry," FAO said. Around 80
million chickens have been slaughtered across Asia, excluding China, to curb
bird flu's spread, it said.
In Thailand, Minister of Natural Resources and the Environment Prapat
Panyachatraksa said Friday that tests showed that a clouded leopard died of
bird flu on 27 Jan 2004 at Khao Khiew Zoo in Chonburi province, 70 km south
of Bangkok, and a tiger fell ill but recovered [he did not say if the tiger
had been confirmed as a case].
The World Health Organization said that if confirmed, this could be the
first known case of the disease found in an exotic animal or a member of
the cat family [See previous item]. 2 separate tests showed the leopard had
succumbed to bird flu, but the exact strain was unclear, Prapat said.
Officials were awaiting the results of a 3rd test. A zoo official, who spoke
on condition of anonymity, said the leopard might have eaten chicken infected
with bird flu. [Presumably the chicken was fed raw -- cooking kills the
virus. - Mod.JW].
Prapat also announced that tests were being carried out on more than 200
cranes that died at Bungboraphet Bird Park in Nakhon Sawan province.
In Taiwan, officials ordered a pet-bird farm in Taiwan's southern Tainan
County to kill about 300 birds, including Swinhoe's pheasants -- a
once-endangered indigenous bird with a short white crest and a blue head.
The culling was ordered after test results showed some of the birds were
infected with H5N2, a less dangerous strain of bird flu that has not jumped
to humans.
10 governments in the region have been dealing with strains of bird flu
since South Korean officials reported an outbreak in December 2003. Some
Asian countries, as well as the United States, are being hit with a milder
bird flu strain not thought to pose a danger to people.
FAO said governments in poorer countries have responded slowly to fight
bird flu because of a lack of resources, such as qualified veterinary
staff. "In addition, the urgently required administrative and political
structures to run an effective emergency campaign are often not yet in
place," it said.
On Friday, the World Bank said it would give Vietnam a USD 10 million loan
to help its poultry industry, which has been ravaged by the flu.
WHO officials have expressed concern that China may also be suffering human
cases given the broad range of poultry infections in that sprawling country,
which has confirmed avian flu in 14 of its 31 regions. China's Agriculture
Ministry reported on Friday confirmed bird flu outbreaks in fowl in 7 more
locations, including Shanghai.
[Byline: Tisha Steyn]
